  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Reply to Friends Park and Jeon Who Sent Inquiries from the Capital
  author: Lee Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I write to you now. Your letter has traveled a thousand leagues to reach me, and I am gladdened to learn that both of you are in good health and spirits. My heart is moved beyond measure.

    This month our forces departed from the Eastern Capital and have taken garrison in Cloud Gate Mountain. The bandit troubles have somewhat subsided, and the camp remains peaceful. My days pass simply—I dig for fresh mushrooms beneath the pines, toast them over fire, and feast upon them. They taste remarkably fine.

    I confess I am but a scholar, untrained in the arts of war. Yet circumstance has pressed me into service as a soldier, trembling in my boots at first. Gradually, however, I have grown accustomed to military life. Even the bow and horse, those martial skills, have begun to show some improvement in my hands of late. Yet should word of this reach the learned circles, I fear I would become the object of great laughter.

    As for drafting proclamations here in camp—the mind grows dim from the trials of battle, not as swift as it was in those days when wine loosened my brush hand and words flowed like water. Still, I cannot claim complete sluggishness; my superiors find little to reproach me for.

    Should opportunity permit and news from home reach me again, I would be most grateful. But my messenger departs in haste, and I cannot say all that lies in my heart. I can only wish that each of you preserve yourselves well. I bow my head in reverence.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Cloud Gate Mountain (雲門山): Located in modern-day North Korea, significant as a strategic garrison position.'
  - key: ''
    value: The scholar's ironic self-deprecation about his newfound martial skills reflects the literati's traditional disdain for military pursuits, a common theme in classical East Asian poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to wine loosening the brush reflects the romantic ideal of the drunken poet whose words flow most beautifully—a contrast to his current strained circumstances.
